3.1  The Indo-Aryan / Dravidian Divide
The translation results reveal a sharp and linguistically meaningful split. For Indo-Aryan languages with Devanagari or closely related scripts—Hindi, Marathi, and Gujarati—translation consistently improves over zero-shot for both models. Mistral-Marathi gains +0.150 F1 (0.420 → 0.570), Mistral-Gujarati gains +0.171 (0.368 → 0.539), and Mistral-Hindi gains +0.111 (0.450 → 0.561). These are the largest absolute F1 gains observed in the translation condition. The mechanism is direct: IndicTrans2 achieves high translation quality for Indo-Aryan pairs given their structural proximity to Hindi, the best-represented Indic language in NMT training corpora. High-quality English input enables both models to summarize in their strongest generation language, recovering the substantial English advantage (F1 = 0.650–0.652) for these languages.
Dravidian languages tell an entirely different story. Translation ​extit{harms} performance relative to zero-shot for Telugu and Kannada under both models, and produces only marginal gains or neutral results for Tamil. Telugu is the worst-affected: Qwen-Telugu F1 falls from 0.450 to 0.241 (−0.209), with hallucination rising from 0.463 to 0.774. Mistral-Telugu falls from 0.282 to 0.200, reaching the lowest single result in the translation condition. The qualitative analysis explains this: IndicTrans2 translation quality for Telugu, Tamil, and Kannada is substantially lower than for Indo-Aryan pairs—morphologically complex verb forms, conditional structures, and clinical terminology are frequently mistranslated or semantically collapsed, producing degraded English that the summarizer cannot recover from. The translation pipeline does not just fail to help; it actively introduces new error types (T8: Mistranslation Cascade; T7: Fabricated Presence/Absence Assertions) that are absent from direct zero-shot inference.
 
