4.1  Magnitude of SFT Gains
The absolute F1 improvements from zero-shot to SFT are large and consistent across all languages. Qwen SFT gains range from +0.127 (English) to +0.406 (Gujarati), with a macro-average improvement of +0.256. Mistral SFT gains are even larger, ranging from +0.117 (English) to +0.487 (Telugu), with a macro-average of +0.328. The larger Mistral gains reflect both the lower Mistral zero-shot baseline and the greater headroom available for improvement. After fine-tuning, the Qwen and Mistral performance gap narrows substantially: at zero-shot, Qwen leads Mistral by 0.086 F1 points; at SFT, the gap closes to 0.014 (0.775 vs. 0.760), suggesting that fine-tuning is highly effective at closing model-level performance gaps driven by pretraining differences.
4.2  SFT Delivers the Largest Gains for the Most Challenging Languages
A critical and clinically important finding is that SFT gains are largest precisely where zero-shot performance was worst. The five largest Qwen SFT gains are: Gujarati (+0.406), Kannada (+0.371), Telugu (+0.358), Tamil (+0.242), and Marathi (+0.246). The five largest Mistral SFT gains are: Telugu (+0.487), Gujarati (+0.401), Kannada (+0.356), Tamil (+0.340), and Assamese (+0.337). In every case, the languages with the largest gains are the same languages that showed the worst zero-shot performance—Dravidian languages and low-resource Indo-Aryan languages.
This is not merely a ceiling effect. The absolute SFT F1 values for these languages are among the highest in the matrix: Qwen-Kannada SFT reaches 0.812, Qwen-Telugu SFT reaches 0.808, and Qwen-Gujarati SFT reaches 0.800. These are competitive with or exceeding the English zero-shot baseline (0.650). The fine-tuning process effectively eliminates the language-family performance gap that was stark at zero-shot: the Dravidian language group, which averaged 0.457 F1 at Qwen zero-shot (versus 0.589 for IA high-resource), averages 0.781 at Qwen SFT—nearly identical to the IA high-resource SFT average of 0.756.
 
