4.4  Safety After Fine-Tuning: Approaching but Not Crossing 3.0
Fine-tuning substantially improves Safety scores across all languages, raising the macro-average from 2.560 to 2.962 (Qwen) and from 2.496 to 2.916 (Mistral). However, the macro-average does not cross 3.0/5.0 for either model, and the per-language picture reveals that only a minority of languages individually exceed this threshold.
Qwen SFT exceeds Safety = 3.0 for Bengali (3.06), English (3.06), Marathi (3.02), and Kannada (3.08). Mistral SFT exceeds 3.0 for English (3.04) and Gujarati (3.00) only. The majority of languages remain just below 3.0 despite substantial safety improvement from the fine-tuning process. Two languages are consistently below 3.0 across both models at SFT: Hindi (Qwen 2.86, Mistral 2.90) and Dogri (Qwen 2.84, Mistral 2.74). This persistent Safety deficit—which is present across all eight experimental conditions—suggests that the clinical safety dimension captures a quality facet that current training objectives and architectures do not fully optimize for, even under supervised fine-tuning on domain-matched data.
Despite dramatic improvements from SFT, Safety remains below 3.0/5.0 on average for both models. The safety gap between Truthfulness and Safety—which measures the dissociation between factual plausibility and clinical actionability—actually widens under SFT (Qwen: +1.19; Mistral: +1.17) compared to zero-shot (Qwen: +0.76; Mistral: +0.60). Models become more truthful faster than they become safer, indicating that safety-specific training objectives (beyond standard instruction fine-tuning) are required for clinical deployment readiness.
4.5  ROUGE-L and BERTScore Under SFT
SFT produces substantial improvements on surface-level metrics as well. Macro-average ROUGE-L rises from 0.1318 to 0.2276 (+0.0958) for Qwen and from 0.1352 to 0.2262 (+0.0910) for Mistral—both representing approximately 70% relative improvement. BERTScore rises from 0.8557 to 0.8828 (+0.0271) for Qwen and from 0.8478 to 0.8796 (+0.0318) for Mistral. These gains indicate that SFT summaries are not merely more entity-complete but also structurally closer to gold summaries in both lexical surface form and semantic content. The joint improvement across all three evaluation tiers—surface metrics, holistic quality dimensions, and entity-level fidelity—confirms that fine-tuning generalizes across the multiple dimensions of clinical summary quality rather than optimizing one at the expense of others.
 
