5.3  The Safety Ceiling: A Cross-Paradigm Finding
One finding is consistent across all eight experimental conditions, both models, and all 10 languages: Safety does not reach 3.0/5.0 as a macro-average in any condition. This is a cross-paradigm result that cannot be attributed to a specific prompting weakness or training limitation. The best macro-average safety score in the entire evaluation is 2.962 (Qwen SFT), which falls 0.038 points below the 3.0 threshold. The safety trend across conditions is: Translation (2.217) < Few-Shot (2.354–2.575) < Zero-Shot (2.496–2.560) < SFT (2.916–2.962).
The safety gap—the difference between Truthfulness and Safety scores—provides additional insight. Under SFT, Truthfulness improves dramatically (to 4.084–4.156) while Safety improves more modestly (to 2.916–2.962), causing the gap to widen from approximately 0.60–0.76 at zero-shot to 1.17–1.19 at SFT. Models learn to produce factually coherent summaries rapidly under fine-tuning, but the safety dimension—which penalizes actionable clinical errors, omitted contraindications, and incomplete treatment plans—requires additional targeted optimization beyond standard next-token prediction on gold summaries. This finding motivates future work on safety-specific fine-tuning objectives, reinforcement learning from clinical expert feedback, and automated safety evaluation frameworks tailored to the multilingual clinical summarization domain.
 
